Lost work hours are only one example of the impacts of extreme heat, especially when sustained over long periodsOthers include agriculture yield losses, the spread of disease-carrying mosquitoes & the increased need for air conditioning with its accompanying energy consumption.

• It Could Become Too Hot to Live in Many Places By the End of the CenturyThis may the most catastrophic of our climate change facts. As of now, only 0.8% of the planet’s land surface has mean annual temperatures above 29°C, mostly in the Sahara Desert and Saudi Arabia

A report from The Lancet found that the number of work hours lost to heat across the globe increased from 199 billion in 2000 to 295 billion in 2020.Of course, daytime outdoor labor is most exposed, which often targets lower-income areas & professions, especially in agriculture.

• We Lost 302.4 Billion Work Hours to Excessive Heat In 2019If you have ever been in humid South East Asia on a hot August day, you will know that working outdoors with shade is barely feasible, and without, simply dangerous.

• Global Warming Is (Partially) ReversibleIf global net emissions were entirely ceased,the warming would gradually reverse but other climate-induced changes would continue for decades if not centuries. For ex. sea level rise would probably take millennia to reverse its course

We can now say with precision how much likelier we made things like the North American summer heatwave which the World Weather Attribution says was “virtually impossible” without climate change as well as the Indian heatwave which experts believe it was made 30 times more extreme

• Attribution Is Now Possible (Extreme Weather)We can now attribute natural disasters to human-driven climate change with certainty. This hasn’t always been the case as a lack of data & refined techniques for detecting made it hard to tell how much we had to do with weather
Some have proposed intentionally disseminating particles into the atmosphere to help reflect more sunlight, but potential unforeseen consequences have prevented us from doing so.

Polluting particles such as PM10 or PM2.5 which cause adverse health effects similar to those of cigarettes actually reflect the sun’s heat.We’ve pumped enough greenhouse gases into the atmosphere to warm it by 1.5C already but fine particles have kept it around 1.1C so far.

• Air pollution Is Both Good and BadIt was recently found that air pollution kills more than 9 million people per year. Developing hotspots in south Asia and Africa will be dealing with poor air quality for years to come, but there is a silver lining.

Since 90s, we’ve lost around 28 trillion tons of ice with todays melt rate standing at 1.2 trillion tons a year.To help you put that into perspective, the combined weight of all human-made things is 1.1 trillion tons. That’s about the same weight as all living things on earth.
• We Are Losing 1.2 Trillion Tons of Ice Each YearThis item on our list of climate change facts can be hard to comprehend because we are dealing with volume beyond our comprehension.

Once again, the ocean comes to our rescue by absorbing about one-third of the carbon in the atmosphere.Before the industrial revolution it was actually a source of carbon & not a sink but the massive amount of CO2 now in the atmosphere has forced it to start absorbing the gas.

• CO2 Is At Its Highest in 2 Million YearsPre-industrial CO2 levels were around 280 parts per million (ppm). Today, we stand close to 420 ppm.The most distant period in time for which we have estimated CO2 levels is around the Ordovician period, 500 million years ago.

The ocean has tremendous volume and heat-storage capacity, which is why some organisms are used to temperatures being quite stable. Of these, coral reefs are particularly sensitive to temperature levels, reason for which many are now dying off.

• The Ocean Absorbs Most of the Heat We ProduceA 2019 study found that oceans had sucked up 90% of the heat gained by the planet between 1971 and 2010. Another found that it absorbed 20 sextillion joules of heat in 2020  – equivalent to two Hiroshima bombs per second.

Only around 125,000 years ago, a time prior to the last ice age, might have had higher temperature than the ones we are currently experiencing. Each of these past warm periods were caused by slow (multi-millennial) orbital variations that are not in play today.

The vertical bar on the left shows the estimated temperature (very likely range) during the warmest multi-century period in the last 100,000 years, which occurred around 6,500 years ago during our current era called the Holocene.

For about 100,000 years, we have been oscillating between glacial (ice ages) and warmer interglacial periods like the one we currently live in. Yet, this is also the warmest multi-century period we have had in this timespan.

• The Last Decade Was the Hottest in 125,000 YearsMost straightforward of our climate change facts: according to the IPCC’s sixth assessment report on the state of our climate, the past decade is likely to have been the hottest period in the last 125,000 years.

How are we so certain?It took a while but climate modelling is now refined enough to predict how things would go without human influence within a margin of error.What we are observing today is beyond that margin of error, therefore proving that we have driven the change.

We shall also expose how the abandonment of Kasese's copper mine has led to the flow of cancer-causing copper tailings - into the only water sources of communities around R. Nyamwamba

If you're interested, please read this open-access manuscript. Please retweet and share it with whoever you might think would find this useful, within the marine space and beyond. Thank you! https://t.co/FH4j8iHDio (13/13)

The health score is simple and easy to communicate and understand. The approach is useful for environmental managers, stakeholders, the public, and scientists and could guide future monitoring, conservation, and restoration actions. (12/13)

The multi-indicator state space approach to assessing ecosystem health is sensitive to subtle changes. It is versatile and can be adapted to any ecosystem where ecological understanding exists. (11/13)
The broad decline in reef ecosystem health was linked to increased sediment cover on the reef and ocean warming. (10/13)

Over the 13 years, the kelp forest persisted. However, we found a general decline in ecosystem health at 5 sites. This was associated with the shortening of the kelp canopy, a collapse of the snail community, and alien species increase (9/13)
If a site's distance in state space from the "optimal" reference grew with time, that reflected a decline in ecosystem health at this site. (8/13)

The distance in state space of each site at each year from the optimal reference point was used as a scalar of health and was standardised to a 0 to 1 score based on the distance between the "optimal" and the "worst" references. - the "health score" (7/13)

We compiled this multi-indicator data into a nine-dimensional state space and calculated the position of each of the 10 monitoring sites in state space and how it changed with time. We modelled "optimal" and "worst" health reference points in state space. (6/13)

In the paper, we proposed the multi-indicator state space approach: Based on the theory of ecosystem health and ecological understanding from the world's temperate reefs and kelp forests from northern New Zealand | #Aotearoa, 9 health indicators were selected. (5/13)

What constitutes a healthy reef? How ecosystem health can be assessed? We used 13 years of reef community monitoring data from a shallow sheltered sediment-laden reef system in Auckland, #NZ's largest city. (4/13) @AklCouncil @AucklandUni

Quantifying ecosystem health is, therefore, challenging, especially given that pristine ecosystems are rare. This is especially true in urban areas, where decades of intensive human impact have resulted in a shifted baseline. (3/13)

Ecosystem health is broadly defined as the well-being of the ecosystem, which is a function of its vigour, organisation, and resilience. This is a highly complex, multi-faceted concept, and no single measurable variable can adequately reflect the health of an ecosystem. (2/13)

The rate of carbon emissions are the highest they’ve been in 66 million years and the amount of warming in the coming decades is expected to be 250 times greater than the average warming during the past century.
However, the rises in temperature and carbon dioxide levels we’ve seen in the past century are extreme and are accelerating.

Over Earth’s history, carbon dioxide levels fluctuate due to volcanic activity or the carbon cycle (animals and bacteria breathe in oxygen and breathe out carbon dioxide while plants do the opposite).

Scientists have known for centuries that gases in Earth’s atmosphere like carbon dioxide and methane act as a greenhouse, preventing a certain amount of heat radiation from escaping back to space. The more carbon dioxide in the atmosphere, the warmer it gets.

Yes, over 97% of scientist agree that humans cause climate change. Humanity’s accelerated burning of fossil fuels and deforestation have led to rapid increases of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere and global warming.

The Doomsday Clock has been widely covered in the media, and its setting is considered an important marker of the world's current state of affairs.
The clock is not a permanent display and is only reset when the Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists holds its biannual meeting to assess the state of the world and decide on a new setting.
The clock is not a prediction of when a global catastrophe will occur, but rather a warning of the current state of the world and the direction it is heading in.
Factors that can influence the setting of the Doomsday Clock include nuclear weapons proliferation, climate change, biotechnology, and cyber threats.
The closest the clock has ever been to midnight was in 1953, when the United States and Soviet Union tested hydrogen bombs within months of each other, setting the clock at two minutes to midnight.
The clock's setting has been adjusted 22 times since its creation, with the most recent adjustment made in 2020, setting the clock at 100 seconds to midnight.

The clock was first created in 1947 by the Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists, a group of scientists and experts who had worked on the Manhattan Project.The clock's original setting was seven minutes to midnight, with midnight representing global catastrophe.
